I created a subclass of ModelSchema, and did something like this in the constructor:
```
		self.complexSetterFields = {}	# a dict of any fields that need to be set with a function
		for key,field in self.fields.items():
			metadata = getattr(field, "metadata", None)
			if metadata and 'complexSetter' in field.metadata:
				self.complexSetterFields[key] = field.metadata['complexSetter']
```

Then I did my own make_instance():
```
	@ma.post_load
	def make_instance(self, data):
		instance = self.instance or self.get_instance(data)
		if instance is not None:
			if self.complexSetterFields:
				for key, value in iteritems(data):
					if key in self.complexSetterFields:
						curr = getattr(instance, key)
						if curr == value:
							pass   # skip setting to existing value
						else:
							ourMethod = self.complexSetterFields[key]
							ourMethod(data, instance, key, value)
							db.session.flush()
					else:   # simply set, like original mm code
						setattr(instance, key, value)
			else:    # normal mm code
				for key, value in iteritems(data):
					try:
						setattr(instance, key, value)
					except:
						print "Error setting [%s] attribute '%s'"%(type(instance), key)
						raise
					#sqlalchemy.orm.attributes.set_attribute(instance, key, value)
			return instance
		
		instance = self.opts.model(**data)
		return instance
```

Now I can do something like this when defining a schema:
```
	myComplexField = ma.fields.Number(complexSetter=lambda data,instance,key,val: setattr(instance, key, val*2 if instance.shouldWeDouble else val) )
```

So I'm passing a function (a lambda in this case) as "complexSettter=" that takes those 4 parameters, and it will get called by my customized make_instance().  In this demo it is a simple check of an attribute on the instance and doubles the value if it is True, but it could do whatever is needed with the original value. This is a bit of a hack, and I didn't dig into the MM internals enough to know if it might fail outside of my simple needs.

